European inflation was slender in food
Rapid inflation, recorded in the euro area, is due firstly to the dwindling increase in the price of foodstuffs.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, registering - after 2.6 percent of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the EU Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only likely to give a 3 percent - Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuer banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decrease, along with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "We have to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene on this issue later.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, struck the record for twelve years; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation occurred in the euro area as a result of galloping food and energy prices.
End-of-wheat quotations increased by 88 per cent and so did soybean contributions reach their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and milk products.
The price of crude oil on the world market rose by 52 percent this year, reaching almost $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from 2.1 percent current to 2.5 percent, but by 2009 it will fall to 1.9 percent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will be maintained in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
