In many hospitals you save with disinfectants
This year several thousand infections have been reported in hospitals primarily due to the improper application of antibiotics.
The circumstances of hygiene prevailing in hospitals, overcrowding of beds and overburdening of staff do not favor the control of infections - says the department doctor-chief of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many hospitals it saves even with disinfectants.
A contact with MRSA has recently been diagnosed in the trauma department of Hospital János.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this hospital at the beginning of the year.
A serious car accident wound was discharged from the hospital and the same patient shortly thereafter had to return to the hospital following the infection with MRSA and since then there has been no significant surgical intervention by the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December of this year, there have been records in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multi-resistant agents - said Karolina Böröcz, a medical chief of department of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents has certainly been recorded, and there is no information.
About two thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, methicillin-oxacillin-resistant.
One third of humans carry in their nose the bacteria of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) without causing any disease.
Infections produced by SA (e.g. inflammation of the throat, tonsilitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once excessively or improperly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics become very antibiotic-resistant bacteria and quickly become infected in inadequate hospital conditions.
They may cause serious hospital infections, such as injuries or septicemia, first of all, to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with the weakened body, to elderly or to those with low weights.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of Hospital János there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection with the epidemic should not be confused, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotics resistant
"These patients are isolated, nursing staff treat them in rubber gloves and masks and there are antibiotics suitable for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but infection in all cases cannot be avoided.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections of MRSA in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of training and infection with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA.
However, the use of microbiological samples is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases come to public light when infections of MRSA are already visible in the patient - said the department doctor-head of the epidemiological center.
The European Union strongly commends the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological tables.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is directed, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Taking microbiological samples is even less common in the case of walking patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
Saves with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, they play a very important role in handwashing, the use of rubber gloves and masks, but also in this sense there are considerable shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is infected by drop transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated for at least a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately it can also be experienced - Karolina Böröcz added - that in hospitals with less favourable economic situation saves with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate prevention measures are carried out, fewer such infections are recorded or the infection of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Programme against MRSA
Treatment of contact with MRSA is a huge expense for the National Sickness Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is fighting against it.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The program seems to have success, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and that of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
