EUR 400 million more for infrastructure
Hungarian finance minister János Veres and vice-president of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit-limit agreements in Budapest on Friday for a total amount of EUR 400 million to finance education, transport and the environment infrastructure as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance in the Hungarian budget for transport and environmental protection projects, which will be made out of the grant of cohesion funds, of which the parties had already signed a credit contract worth EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit contract is also used to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this Hungary target on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later by extending the credit agreement.
The parties signed a contract for EUR 50 million for innovations, which will be used primarily for the University of Debrecen innovation and research project.
During the talks they also covered the theme of the construction of the 4th Metro line.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary finalises details of Metro financing with the EU, the subject will be dealt with again if it is necessary or not to modify the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this may take place early in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest of the appropriations is in line with EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charge for keeping the credit available to the debtor.
