Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, meetings at the expert level will end on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue negotiations at the level of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world discuss the Bali Road Map, which provides for post-emission reduction efforts, established in the Kyoto Protocol, which runs until 2012.
Discussions are currently taking place on the particular issue between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not wish to negotiate on precise figures at the moment, although it tends to reach the agreement that compared with the situation in 1990, by 2020, the emissions of greenhouse gases will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another important theme of the conference is that if industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are prepared to provide material and technological assistance to countries that need it.
A further agreement was reached on aid to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be headed by a management board consisting of 16 members, probably within the United Nations Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes "Piac es Profit".
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent at the 1990 level by 2020, whether or not the "after 2012 agreement" will be signed and is prepared to commit to reducing even 30 percent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to decrease by 5.2 per cent, within which 15 EU Member States committed themselves to reaching 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce the greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent over the period 1985-87, which our country will meet - notes the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
This is a lot of what is at stake in Bali, since within two years the international long-term climate policy agreement will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed by after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, the need of which was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the UN international scientific association dealing with climate change, which was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
With this, emissions reduction would be delayed and an increase of more than 2°C of the average temperature of the Earth could not be prevented, since according to scientists there would be immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British Army recruited on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) was the one that took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are loading videos about their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These tapes with mini cameras mounted on helmets are controlled in the general Kandahar operations body, then sent to London to be loaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are already 139 recordings from Air Force soldiers that have been loaded in this way to the Internet and its "channel" has already been seen by over 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in spring 2007 as "headquarters defence" and publishes videos of actions carried out in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the British Community of Nations (Commonwealth Office) and multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the air force had loaded the videos with recruitment objectives, but in the view of the Ministry of Defence, they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This kind of propaganda hardly costs anything compared to conventional recruitment television spots - told BBC defense expert Gordon Mackenzie - instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for being the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned that, in addition to the carefully edited and censored recordings, amateur videos appear in the distributor, for example about the death of soldiers: in the "official" advertising films, a bit hypocritical, the officers speak as much loss as possible, without however presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have been loaded on the Internet from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army has only recently taken advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with video games of shooting, downloadable for free, called America's Army, in which in the middle of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly instead of the soldiers.
