The forces of the giant strike are gathering
The League Trade Unions and the National Federation of Labour Commissions will form a strike commission on Friday to coordinate the Monday strike that will last indefinitely.
On Saturday there will be a protest rally, while on Monday - the day on which the final vote on the public health law will be held - the work stop will begin.
This action will certainly cause great difficulties in transport, as the rail traffic will be completely stopped and workers from the Budapest Collective Transport Company will also be on strike until 13 hours.
In the afternoon of Friday, the League Trade Unions will report on the details of their Monday strike that will be held jointly with the National Federation of Labour Commissions.
The strike commission of the LIGA and the National Machinery Union will also be set up to coordinate Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a protest rally will be held, while on Monday the participating unions will be pronounced on an indefinite strike, if no agreement is reached with the government.
This means that - on the day of the parliamentary vote on the public health law - they did not report on the date of the end of the strike initiated.
If the National Assembly disapproves the public health law, the unions will immediately withdraw their appeal to strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike commissions will meet and decide on the future.
On the basis of the agenda of Monday of the National Assembly, it is also possible that only public health law is voted on at night hours, or at best close to midnight.
As a result of the strike to begin on Monday, significant difficulties will have to be encountered in transport: in the railways it will no longer work indefinitely, in the morning some part of the collective transport of Budapest and more than half of the interurban transport of buses of the Volán companies will be stopped.
At the same time, there will be a closing of half of the roads at many points in the country.
Numerous trade unions and civil organizations have joined the strike, their names are constantly updated on the League website.
Some unions announced their strike for time indefinite, others for time defined.
Until Thursday afternoon, the State Railway and the Free Railway Workers' Union (SLTF) were unable to reach agreement even on minimum services, although, as Christmas parties are approaching, they are increasingly the people who travel on trains.
According to information received so far, from the start of the day until 13 hours the workers of the Budapest Collective Transport Company will be on strike, the Budapest Airports from 7 to 9 am, will hold a four-hour strike the LIGA Trade Unions of the Electrical Industry and Thermal Energy, the Educators' Trade Unions called for a 2-hour strike and the Democratic Union of the Educators from 2 to 8 hours.
The Hungarian Association of Physicians will take a national strike at alternative times and the Democratic Union of Health and Social Sector Workers (SDTSSS) who form part of the Trade Union Cooperation Forum will hold a two-hour strike of warning.
The most important of the four demands made by the League is that the government withdraws its proposal for public health reform and puts a new conception into a social debate.
The second demand is to gradually introduce the new form of calculation of pensions which will enter into force next year.
The third is that they ensure, even before 2010, for advanced pensions, the possibility that occupations that deserve it may enter the system.
The fourth reason for the strike is that the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (SLTF), which is part of the League Trade Unions, does not accept the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport on the railway lines and expect another different proposal.
Political Capital[b1]: In the country the risk for the Hungarian Guard is increased
According to the Risk Analysis Division (Risk Analysis Division) of the Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, formed in August this year with the support of the Better Hungary Movement, has increased the political risk of Hungary and the region from a number of points of view.
The company's "risk warning" writes: in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is the fact that "with the escalation of ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Gypsies of Hungary, even in the short term violent ethnic confrontations can occur".
The main reason for this is that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy is probably the provocation of an event of this nature - the representative of the research institute added.
They stated that all this was due to one of the main shortcomings of the protagonists of Hungarian political life: "the protagonists of public life yielded the public debate of the Gypsy problem to the representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who were able to base their political strategy on the discrepancies between Roma and Hungarians."
This aggravates the problem, prevents normal dialogue, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of the outbreak of violent conflicts - they estimate.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activity of the National Guard, as a result of the great attention of the national and international media, "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, especially with regard to the stability and democratic development of the country".
They remind us that since the fall of 2006 there has been increasing publicity and momentum for the reorganization of the radical and extreme right-wing groups of Hungary and that since the summer of 2007 many organizations have been established in the country that are self-defining of "national self-defence associations".
