A Weighted Memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the destinations of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are free to access.
The 47 million file documents, stored over 27 km of shelf to Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not so far accessible only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e., individually and nominally, at the request of an old victim or his right-to-be.
The eleven managing States - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been concluded, the opening is effective since yesterday.
Sensitive Information
Access by historians to Bad Arolsen will allow search " particularly on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced workers " , explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, a number of States, such as Germany, had opposed the openness of these nomination documents to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental hangicap of certain victims of deportation.
Records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the countrymen deported or subjected to compulsory work and, eventually, to provide them with proof of their detention, in order to open the way for their compensation.
Today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected from these documents," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Research Centre on Anti-Semitism at the University of Berlin in 2006.
