Venus: twin brother of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most like the Earth, something that had not been raised so far. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and ravines in the poles, the same ones that appear also in winter on Earth.
For three decades now, researchers had suspected that there could be rays in Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus the rays lie at a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles told the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller's life, the rays caused life on Earth: the storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, for their part, had given rise to amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it is not so: if one day there were to live there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times greater than on Earth and on the surface reign temperatures of 500°C, oscillating so that temperatures can be reached below zero.
"Perhaps Venus is a "diabolic" twin on Earth, but it remains a twin," Russell said.
The main goal of the mission "Venus Express" is to answer the question why Venus, so much like the Earth for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there have been no special missions, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for the investigation of Venus.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many "Nature" articles, according to researchers' opinion, not only emphasize the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighbouring planets have more common features with the Earth than we had assumed," says ESA.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, researchers also discovered in the southern polar region a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon recalls the wind flows in the high terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost so large.
This planet also known as the sunrise star or the evening star orbits around the Sun nearly 225 days.
But its rotational period is slower: one day in Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bar is not much like Earth, scientists are based on the basis that both planets had formed in the same conditions.
On the two planets water had been agglomerated that on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it was disoccupied in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, in Venus forms most of the atmosphere.
