Currently the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that weighs on Warhol's list of works.
Most of the ninety-four Brillo-Box "type" on this list are false.
After a few months ago the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of Brillo-Boxes of 1968 by Andy Warhol, the Museum Moderna Museet in Stockholm carried out internal investigations and came to disappointing conclusions: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director of the Museum Pontus Hultén gave to the Museum Moderna Museet, are false, and almost one hundred of the others of "Type Stockholm", who are in circulation in the international art market, also result.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted the boxes of red, blue and white wood, with the same sample that had soap powder cartons "Brillo".
According to Warhol, at the exhibition of his 1968 works in the Museum Moderna Museet were exposed hundreds of flashlights-boxes of cardboard. These did not make them Warhol (because of the expenses), but were brought directly from the paper factory of "Brillo".
These were not works of art, but examples (which were only objects) exposed.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed to produce in Sweden a Brilliant wooden box, but were not exposed at the Modern Museum museum.
Witnesses of those times now speak of that almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auctions as originals of the "Brillo-Boxes" of "Stocolmo type" authorized by Andy Warhol.
In auctions some of them were bought for more than $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous director of the Pontus Hultén museum made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden were produced and exposed nearly a hundred of the wooden boxes Warhol left to him.
But actually, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hulten and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time Warhol had already died three years ago.
